[[File:Director's Headshot - Flickr - Eye Steel Film.jpg|thumb|Lixin Fan in 2009]] '''Lixin Fan''' (範立欣, Fàn Lìxīn), b. March 1977, in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]] province, China,<ref name="Miqu ">[http://www.miiqu.net/star/51638 範立欣] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418051042/http://www.miiqu.net/star/51638 |date=2016-04-18 }} 覓 趣 (Miqu)</ref> is a [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada-based [[documentary film]] director with the Canadian production company [[EyeSteelFilm]] and previously a producer/journalist at China’s state broadcaster [[China Central Television|CCTV]].
== Early life and career == Lixin Fan was born and raised in Wuhan and attended the Huazhong University of Science and Engineering, graduating with a degree in English at the age of twenty-one. during its years of rapid economic development. He began his career as a journalist with the government owned national TV broadcaster [[China Central Television]] (CCTV).<ref name="Miqu " /> While traveling the country Fan witnessed social and economic inequalities spurred by China’s rapid economic expansion. As a result, he became a documentary filmmaker with a focus on social issues.<ref name="POV">[https://www.pbs.org/pov/lasttrainhome/bio.php "Bio: Lixin Fan"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130802075439/http://www.pbs.org/pov/lasttrainhome/bio.php |date=2013-08-02 }}, [[POV (TV series)|P.O.V.]] TV series website</ref>
Lixin was editor of the 2002 film ''[[To Live Is Better Than To Die]]'' <ref>{{imdb title|0343105|To Live Is Better Than To Die}}</ref><ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/280939/To-Live-is-Better-Than-to-Die/overview "Overview: To Live Is Better Than To Die"], ''The New York Times''</ref> about China’s [[AIDS]] crisis which was featured in the [[Sundance Film Festival]] and broadcast on [[BBC]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] and [[PBS]].
He also worked as an associate producer, sound recordist, and translator on the acclaimed 2007 feature documentary ''[[Up the Yangtze]]''.
His 2009 debut feature documentary film ''[[Last Train Home (film)|Last Train Home]]'' won several awards in the category of documentary filmmaking.
==Awards== *2009: Won Best Feature Documentary at the 22nd annual [[International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam]] (IDFA)<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/canadian-documentary-wins-international-prize/article1382157/ The Globe and Mail: "Canadian documentary wins international prize"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205211814/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/canadian-documentary-wins-international-prize/article1382157/ |date=2009-12-05 }}</ref> for his debut film ''Last Train Home'' *2009: Won Cinémathèque Québécoise Best Quebec film award at the [[Rencontres internationales du documentaire de Montréal]] (RIDM) also for ''Last Train Home''
