{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}
{{Redirect|SPAB|the former United States administrative entity|Supply Priorities and Allocation Board}}
The '''Society for the Protection of Ancient Buildings''' ('''SPAB''') (sometimes known as '''Anti-Scrape'''<ref>{{cite book|first=E. P.|last=Thompson|authorlink=E. P. Thompson|year=1976|title=William Morris: Romantic to Revolutionary|publisher=Pantheon|quote=The Society, which Morris dubbed "Anti-Scrape...|location=[[New York City|New York]]|isbn=0-394-73320-7|page=228}}</ref>) is an [[amenity society]] founded by [[William Morris]], [[Philip Webb]] and others, in 1877; to oppose what they saw as destructive 'restoration' of ancient buildings then occurring in [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] [[England]]; 'ancient' being used in the wider sense of 'very old' rather than the more usual modern one of 'pre-[[medieval]]'.

Morris was particularly concerned about the practice, which he described as 'forgery', of attempting to return functioning buildings to an idealised state from the distant past, which often involved the removal of elements added in their later development, and which Morris saw as contributing to their interest as documents of the past.  Instead, he proposed that ancient buildings should be repaired, not restored, so that their entire history would be protected as [[cultural heritage]].  Today, these principles are widely accepted.
[[File:William Morris by Sir William Blake Richmond.jpg|thumb|200px|Portrait of [[William Morris]], founder of SPAB, by [[William Blake Richmond]]]]

==Organisation and activities==
Today, the SPAB still operates according to Morris's original manifesto.  It campaigns, advises, runs training programmes and courses, conducts research and publishes information.  As one of the [[Amenity society|National Amenity Societies]], the Society is a statutory consultee on alterations to [[Listed Building|listed buildings]], and by law must be notified of any application in England and Wales to demolish in whole or part any listed building.<ref>{{citation|author=[[Department for Communities and Local Government]]|title=Arrangements for handling heritage applications Direction 2015|date=24 March 2015|url=https://www.GOV.uk/government/publications/arrangements-for-handling-heritage-applications-direction-2015|website=www.GOV.uk|publisher=[[Government of the United Kingdom|HM Government]]|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>  It currently has c. 8,500 members (2012).  The Society also has a branch in [[Scotland]].

The society's Mills Section is the only British national body concerned with the protection, repair and continued use of traditional [[windmill]]s and [[watermill]]s; [[Ken Major]] carried out much work on its behalf.

The society, which is a registered charity, is based at 37 [[Spitalfields|Spital Square]], [[London|LONDON]] [[London E1|E1]] 6DY, [[England]].

For its dedicated service to heritage, the society was awarded the [[European Union Prize for Cultural Heritage / Europa Nostra Awards|European Union Prize for Cultural Heritage / Europa Nostra Award]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://EuropaNostra.org/laureates-2012/|title=2012 EU Prize for Cultural Heritage / Europa Nostra Awards – Category 3 - Dedicated service|website=EuropaNostra.org|publisher=[[Europa Nostra]]|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://EuropaNostra.org/awards/89/|title=The Society for the Protection of Ancient Buildings (SPAB)|website=EuropaNostra.org|publisher=[[Europa Nostra]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://Europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-12-254_en.htm|title=Winners of 2012 EU Prize for Cultural Heritage / Europa Nostra Awards announced|website=Europa.eu|publisher=[[European Commission]] - press release|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>

