{{Distinguish|Centennial Fountain}} [[File:Victoria Centennial Fountain, Victoria, British Columbia, Canada 01.jpg|thumb|right|The fountain in 2018]] '''Victoria Centennial Fountain''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bFe7anFMjcQC&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Portrait of Greater Victoria and Southern Vancouver Island|first=Chris|last=Cheadle|date=4 March 2018|publisher=Heritage House Publishing Co|accessdate=4 March 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=49074|title=The Victoria Centennial Fountain Historical Marker|publisher=|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> also known as '''Back Fountain''' or simply '''Centennial Fountain''', is installed outside the [[British Columbia Parliament Buildings]] in [[Victoria, British Columbia]].<ref>https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/GC/article/view/11087/11746</ref> The fountain was designed by Robert Savery in 1962, and commemorates the four colonies and territories that formed British Columbia. The [[bronze sculpture]]s of a bear, eagle, gull, sea otter, raven, and wolf represent the province's geography and history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leg.bc.ca/content-peo/Documents/Legislative-Assembly-Outdoor-Walking-Tour-English.pdf |title=Documents|website=leg.bc.ca}}</ref>
